did.unittitle: Graphic Communications International Union, Local 767M records

bioghist.p: Labor organization of the printing industry began as early as 1836, with the first meeting of the National Typographical Society, later renamed the International Typographical Union (ITU) in Washington, D.C. However, it wasn’t until the late 1800s that mechanization transformed the printing industry into a full-scale trade with craft specialization. Newspaper printing and commercial printing became distinct trades. By the turn of the century several separate printing unions had emerged or seceded from the ITU, including the International Printing Pressmen Union of North America (IPPU) in 1897 and the Amalgamated Lithographers of America (ALA) in 1915. Union membership flourished in the first half of the 20th century, and the unions were able to operate alone. As union membership declined in the later half of century, a series of mergers occurred. The International Printing and Graphic Communications Union (IPGCU) resulted in 1973 from the merger of the IPPU and the International Stereotypers’ and Electroplaters’ Union (IS&EU). In 1983, the IPGCU merged with the Graphic Arts International Union (GAIU) to form the Graphic Communications International Union (GCIU). In 2005, the GCIU decided to merge with the 1.1 million member Teamster union.

The first printing union in Seattle was the International Brotherhood of Bookbinders (IBB) in 1900. Seven years later, the Seattle Web Printing Pressmen & Assistants’s Union No. 26 was formed. In 1963, Local No. 26 merged with five other Washington printers’ unions to create the Washington state Joint Crafts Council. GCIU branch 767-M was the result of the 1985 merger of PH & PPU Local 50, GCIU Local 26N and GCIU Local 530M. In 1996, GCIU Local 292-M of Portland, Oregon merged with GCIU 767-M. Additionally, between 2002 and 2003, GCIU branches in Bremerton (367-M), Olympia (182-C) and Aberdeen (262-C) merged with Local 767-M, further strengthening the Seattle branch. In 2005, 767-M merged with the Teamster Union. 767-M still exists today.

scopecontent.p: This collection documents the various activities of several branches of the Graphic Communications Conference of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters located in the Pacific Northwest of the United States. The collection spans from 1908-2011, with the bulk of the materials dated post-1970. This collection contains papers that originated in the Seattle branch 767-M of the GCIU, as well as documents that were collected at the time of its creation as well as through subsequent mergers. The documents are from several branches within the state of Washington (Seattle, Aberdeen, Tacoma and Olympia), as well as Portland, Oregon. The oldest files are from Seattle Web Pressmen’s Union No. 26. The collection details the activities of the Union and its members, as well as the relations between the Union and employers. The largest part of the collection documents Contracts and Contract Negotiations (Series III), shining a light on the issues that were most pertinent to both the Union and employers, as well as the changes over time in the way contracts were negotiated. While many of the documents related to medical and financial benefits can be found in these contract files, the remainder are detailed in Benefits (series VII). Of particular note are the Legal Files (Series V), which offer insight into the various arbitration and grievance cases brought up by the Union and the resulting settlements. Further details into the communication between employers and the Union, as well as contact between multiple branches of the Union, can be drawn from Correspondence (Series II). The day to day workings of several earlier branches of the Union can be assessed from the Executive Board and General Union Minutes/By-Laws (Series I), Office Files (Series VI) and Financial Records (Series VII). In addition, Merger Files (Series IV) highlight the policies related to various Union mergers that led up to the 2004 iteration of the GCIU.

arrangement.p: This collection is arranged into 8 series:
Series I: Executive Board and General Union Minutes/By-Laws, 1908-2001

The series are arranged by document format or function and then further arranged by their creator. Within these sub-series, files are arranged chronologically by date of the oldest document in the file. Due to the file management of the Union, there is some overlap between series. For example, many of the files from Contracts/Contract Negotiation (Series III) contain correspondence unrelated to contract negotiations, which would otherwise belong in Correspondence (Series II).

separatedmaterial.p: Photographic prints, film reels, and videocassette tapes were extracted from this accession and placed in the Graphic Communications International Union, Local 767M Visual Materials Collection (PH 1150). This collection contains approximately 30 photographic prints, 3 film reels and 37 video cassette tapes.

otherfindaid.p: The visual materials that form part of this collection are described and indexed in A Guide to the Graphic Communications International Union, Local 767M Photographs and Moving Images .

scopecontent.p: Series I includes extensive minutes of Seattle Web Pressmen’s Union No. 26, as well as the minutes of a handful of local union branches. This series also includes the By-Laws of a few local unions dated 1970-1993.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by function, and further arranged within each sub-series numerically according to the local union number of the originating body: Sub-series A: Minutes, 1908-2001; Part 1: Executive Board Meeting Minutes, 1923-1989; Part 2: General Union Meeting Minutes, 1908-2001; Sub-series B: By-Laws, 1970-1993.

scopecontent.p: Series III includes contracts between various unions and employers, as well as memorandum, minutes, correspondence and voting records that relate to contract negotiations. The bulk of these files originated from Local 767-M, although many contracts relate to other local unions. Also included are disclaimers of interest, which give insight into why employers and unions decided to end contracts.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by function: Subseries A: Contracts/Contract Negotiations, 1911-2011; Subseries B: Disclaimers of Interest-Local 767-M. Subseries A is further divided by creator and arranged chronologically: Part 1: Seattle Web Pressmen's Union No. 26, 1911-1985; Part 2: Aberdeen-Hoquiam Pressmens Union No. 262, 1951-1993; Part 3: Local 767-M Contracts, 1972-2011; Part 4: Local 87-B, 1975; Part 5: Local 202, 1975-1985; Part 6: Local 530, 1971-1991; Part 7: Joint Crafts Council, 1981-2006; Part 8: Local 292-M, 1986-1992; Part 9: Local 149-B, 1987-1994. Within each of these sub-series, files are arranged alphabetically according to employer name. Part 10: Blank Printing Contracts is located at the end of the series.

scopecontent.p: Series IV contains files related to the mergers of local unions, as well as a handful of files related to the mergers of Mail-Well, Inc., a company which was represented by Local 767-M.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by originating body: Subseries A: Union Mergers, 1942, 1963-2004; Subseries B: Mail Well, Inc. Mergers, 1993-2002. Within each subseries, files are arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.p: Series V includes arbitrations between Seattle Web Pressmen’s Union no. 26 and the various employers it dealt with. The series also documents the grievance cases between various unions and employers that were brought before the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and other official employment commissions. Most cases relate to unfair labor practices or petitions for decertification. While the outcome of these grievances varies greatly, all cases offer insight into the types of problems faced by unions, employees and employers.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by function: Subseries A: Arbitrations with Seattle Web Pressmen's Union No. 26, 1911-1953; Subseries B: Grievances, 1980-2001. Subseries B: Grievances, is further divided by case type: Part 1: Unfair Labor Practice Cases, 1980-1981, 1997-2009; Part 2: Petitions for Decertification, 1988-2001; Part 3: Miscellaneous Grievances, 1987-2005. Cases are arranged chronologically within each subseries.

arrangement.p: The series is divided by function: Subseries A: Membership Files, 1908-1967, 1979-1996; Subseries B: Graphic Communications International Union Local 262-C Elections, 1983-1999; Subseries C: Newspapers, 1963-2001; Subseries D: Training, circa 1950s, 1965-1969, 1999. Membership files are arranged chronologically within the subseries. Subseries D: Training is divided by function and arranged chronologically: Part 1: Technical Education Correspondence Courses, circa 1950s; Part 2: Newspaper Manning-Types of Presses [Book], 1965-1969; Part 3: City of Seattle Apprenticeship Program, 1990; Part 4: American Envelope Safety Procedure Proposal, 1992; Part 5: Scott’s Green Book, undated.
